Limit of a deterministic sequence
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\color blue
Mathematical
\series default
\color inherit
 
\series bold
\color blue
limit
\series default
\color inherit
 at infinity for 
\series bold
\color blue
deterministic
\series default
\color inherit
 
\series bold
\color blue
sequences
\series default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}x_{n}=L
\]

\end_inset

means that we can make sure that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vert x_{n}-L|<\epsilon\qquad\Longleftrightarrow\qquad x_{n}\in(L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)
\]

\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, by choosing 
\series bold
\color blue
a large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series default
\color inherit
.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=\left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}x_{n}=e\approx2.7183$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 are random variables, cannot guarantee that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert X_{n}-L|<\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
